- Dr Evans has also contributed to the Government Chief Scientific Adviser's annual report. Each year, a report is commissioned in an area where 'science is thought to add insight to topical issues'. This year's theme is 'resource efficiency' and Dr Evans' contribution draws on (and so cites) project outputs.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>19A94471-DDA3-472F-9F1B-A7CAD328F026</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56d5d0897f7763.11040092</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment,Retail</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The project has developed understandings of household food waste and advanced perspectives that look beyond the choices of individual consumers to consider the social organisation of consumption, everyday life and meal occasions. We analysed a survey of c.70,000 Tesco customers as well as a survey of eating habits in the UK completed by c.2800 online panel members. This allowed us to explore the relationship between the organisation of meal occasions, the production of leftovers, and waste generation. For each meal, detail was gathered on a range of elements and we grouped these into temporal (e.g. day of the week, time of day, and duration of the meal), contextual (e.g. with whom, and where the meal was eaten), and preparatory factors (e.g. where the food or ingredients were from, how the ingredients were stored, method of preparation). All of these factors were found to have an effect on the production of leftovers. For example:

- Contextual factors: Compared with meals eaten alone, meals eaten with household members are over twice as likely to produce leftovers (2.331***), meals with friends almost 3 times (2.890***), and meals with non-household family members almost 3.5 times as likely to have leftovers (3.439***). When a combination of people ate together, the likeliness of there being leftovers increases fivefold (5.115***)
- Temporal factors: Compared with morning meals, food is more likely to be left following afternoon meals (2.345***) and even more so following evening meals (2.647***). Compared with meals lasting less than 10 minutes, meals lasting 10-19 minutes are 53.4% more likely to produce leftovers (1.534***) and meals lasting longer than an hour are seven times more likely to produce leftovers (7.098***)
- Preparatory factors: Leftovers are more likely when meals are made using ingredients stored in the fridge (1.503***) or items that have just been bought (2.043***). Meals are made using a mix of cooking methods, but meals containing items ready to eat are less likely to produce leftovers (0.548***) whereas leftovers are more likely when meals are prepared on the hob (1.557***) and the oven (2.079***). 

Taken together, this suggests the more socially significant a meal is - such as a dinner party with family and friends (as compared to a ready meal eaten alone) - the more likely it is that there will be leftovers that are at risk of going to waste. Our analysis suggests that the likelihood of leftovers being wasted (rather than eaten) is explained almost exclusively by a single variable: how much food is left over. Compared with meals where 30 to 50 per cent was left over, meals with 10 to 30 per cent left over are 19 times more likely to be wasted (19.471**) and leftovers from meals with seemingly insignificant amounts (i.e. less than 10 per cent left over) are 130 times more likely to enter the waste stream (130.329***). No meal with more than 50 per cent left over was sent to waste.

The project also conducted 33 interviews with 38 stakeholders in order to explore the ways in which the challenge of food waste reduction is being framed, interpreted and responded to by engaged constituencies (including policy makers, third sector organisations, campaigners and consultants) with a specific focus on the interface of households and retailers. This was complemented by our observations at a number of food waste conferences, and by hosting our own multi-stakeholder workshop. We marked the end of the project by staging a public event and a discussion - led by an expert panel (including representatives from major retailers, NGOs and think tanks) - on the relationships between food waste and transitions towards a sustainable food system. We found that contemporary responses to the challenge of food waste reduction are characterized two distinct waves (2007 - 2013; 2013 - present), marked by their differences in the configuration of relationships between relevant constituencies, and by the ways in which they construct and mobilize 'the consumer'. While the initial responses (2007 -2013) framed the challenge in terms of individual consumer responsibilities and behaviour change, our analysis suggests that during the second wave (2013 - present), a multi-stakeholder coalition rapidly developed around the issue. Unlike many contentious social and environmental challenges, in which there are rival problem framings, we found a broad consensus around an ensemble of shared ideas and understandings. Crucially, there is widespread recognition that responsibility for food waste reduction is distributed throughout the food chain and that the links between parts of the system are key. 

Our analysis suggests that the emergence of this food waste coalition was enabled by a 'perfect storm' of issues in which concerns about austerity, food price inflation, food poverty, food security, and climate change all came together at the same time. We also identify a number of other 'enabling conditions' including: 

- The importance of issue lifecycles: Food waste rose to prominence at a point when wider issues of waste - e.g. household recycling - had already reached a level of maturity. 
- The lack of counter-constituencies: Crucial to the emergence of the food waste coalition has been the lack of competing framings of the issue (for example from large businesses).
- Previous campaigning and agenda setting: The initial responses wave of food waste campaigning - with its emphasis on the responsibilised consumer - may have served the important purpose of driving the issue of food waste up the agenda and securing the participation and action of major retailers. Retailers are currently assuming responsibilities for waste reduction upstream (with suppliers) and downstream (with consumers). 
- The role of honest brokers and trusted intermediaries: The food waste coalition would not have been possible without WRAP-whose credibility with business, commitment to evidence and arm's length connection to government facilitated agenda setting, awareness raising, and a neutral forum for collaboration and consensus building

The project ended by suggesting that experiences and lessons from the study of food waste reduction (see above) might be instructive for thinking about broader transitions to sustainability in food systems.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our findings re: the organisation of meal occasions, the production of leftovers and waste generation are instructive for a number of academic debates. Principally, they extend the sociological literature on household and consumer food waste that has hitherto been dominated by qualitative and ethnographic studies. Allied to this, they extend the literature that applies insights from theories of practice to the study of household sustainability and behaviour change. The methodological techniques developed in this project illustrate strategies for mobilizing theories of practice empirically using quantitative data. Our findings also contribute to more general sociological understandings of food, eating and the temporal organization of everyday life. In terms of practical applications, these findings extend the evidence base on why household and consumers waste food. Insights from quantitative as well as qualitative studies are important for groups (policy makers, NGOs, firms, campaigners, households) who are involved in efforts to reduce household and consumer food waste. Our findings advocate distinguishing between the cause and location of waste; focusing on shared conventions around food and eating, and thinking about where, when and how meals are eaten. 

Our findings re: the ways in which the challenge of food waste reduction is being framed, interpreted and responded are instructive for a different set of academic debates. Principally they offer empirically grounded sociological insights into supermarkets and extend the literature on the relationships between firms and civil society. The project was particularly successfully in obtaining access to major retailers and so it illustrates useful strategies for researching and collaborating with commercial partners (see Evans 2015). Our project contributes to the sociological literature on sustainable consumption and behaviour change by suggesting that more attention is paid to the discursive figure of 'the consumer' and the changing ways in which it is strategically deployed by a range of collective actors. In terms of practical applications, our findings may be of use to stakeholders (firms, governments, transnational organizations, NGOs, citizens) who are involved in thinking about transitions to greater sustainability in food systems. Our findings advocate the importance of 'the consumer' as proxy, recognition for distributed responsibility, a focus on issue lifecycles, and support for/investment in vehicles for coalition building.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>2EB9825A-1935-42E2-A37B-B441E6A15203</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>55fbff7f340709.59495571</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment,Government, Democracy and Justice,Retail</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.sci.manchester.ac.uk/library/evans-d-welch-d-2015-food-waste-transitions-consumption-retail-and-collaboration-towards</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>096E67C7-7B23-4DC6-B206-DA31D51258E5</gtr:id><gtr